<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="145" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,258,1981]" pageId="2" pageNumber="145">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,321,798,823]" pageId="2" pageNumber="145">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
The new species belongs to the 
<taxonomicName box="[704,852,798,822]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Cryphia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="145" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="salomonis">
<emphasis box="[704,852,798,822]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="145">B. salomonis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species-group, being externally most similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Treitschke, 1825" authorityName="Treitschke" authorityYear="1825" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Bryophila" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="145" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="miltophaea">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="145">B. miltophaea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. By genital structure the new species is close relative of 
<taxonomicName authority="Staudinger, 1881" authorityName="Staudinger" authorityYear="1881" box="[948,1303,834,859]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Bryophila" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="145" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="plumbeola">
<emphasis box="[948,1100,835,859]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="145">B. plumbeola</emphasis>
Staudinger, 
<number box="[1247,1303,835,859]" pageId="2" pageNumber="145" value="1881.0">1881</number>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[1321,1397,834,859]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 6" captionStartId="1.[151,264,1789,1812]" captionTargetBox="[191,1413,212,1759]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[151,1436,195,1765]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 6. Bryophila spp., adults. 1, B. kaszabi, holotype male, W Mongolia, Hundijn-Gol riv. (OPB); 2, B. kaszabi, paratype female, W Mongolia, Uenchijn-Gol riv. (AVB); 3, B. kaszabi,, paratype female, Hundijn-Gol riv. (AVB); 4, B. plumbeola, after Hampson (1908); 5, B. miltophaea, male, Kyrgyzstan, Naryn (ZISP); 6, B. miltophaea, male, Kyrgyzstan, Alai Mts. (OPB)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/230793/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="145">
Figs 
<number box="[1381,1397,835,859]" pageId="2" pageNumber="145" value="4.9">4</number>
</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1413,1428,835,859]" captionStart="FIGURES 7 – 11" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1864,1887]" captionTargetBox="[153,1415,195,1840]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,195,1843]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 7 – 11. Bryophila spp., male and female genitalia. 7, B. kaszabi, male genitalia, holotype, slide OP 2222 m Pekarsky; 8, B. miltophaea, male genitalia, slide OP 0163 m Pekarsky; 9, B. plumbeola, male genitalia, holotype, slide MB 244 Boursin; 10, B. kaszabi, female genitalia, paratype, slide OP 0626 f Pekarsky; 11, B. miltophaea, female genitalia, slide OP 0164 f Pekarsky." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/230794/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="145">9</figureCitation>
) having narrow valva with pointed apex. It differs markedly from all members of the species group in its external and genital features. Externally 
<taxonomicName authority="Treitschke, 1825" authorityName="Treitschke" authorityYear="1825" box="[510,625,907,931]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Bryophila" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="145" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="kaszabi">
<emphasis box="[510,625,907,931]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="145">B. kaszabi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[641,709,906,931]" captionStart="FIGURES 7 – 11" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1864,1887]" captionTargetBox="[153,1415,195,1840]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,195,1843]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 7 – 11. Bryophila spp., male and female genitalia. 7, B. kaszabi, male genitalia, holotype, slide OP 2222 m Pekarsky; 8, B. miltophaea, male genitalia, slide OP 0163 m Pekarsky; 9, B. plumbeola, male genitalia, holotype, slide MB 244 Boursin; 10, B. kaszabi, female genitalia, paratype, slide OP 0626 f Pekarsky; 11, B. miltophaea, female genitalia, slide OP 0164 f Pekarsky." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/230794/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="145">
Fig. 
<number box="[694,709,907,931]" pageId="2" pageNumber="145" value="7.0">7</number>
</figureCitation>
) differs from the similar species by more expressed light medial area, less pointed apex of forewing and less skewed outer margin. In the males, 
<taxonomicName authority="Treitschke, 1825" authorityName="Treitschke" authorityYear="1825" box="[1123,1243,942,966]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Bryophila" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="145" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="kaszabi">
<emphasis box="[1123,1243,942,966]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="145">B. kaszabi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from all congeners by its very characteristic, almost straight ventral side of distal half of the valva and the acute apex with pointed extension. In addition, the new species differs from 
<taxonomicName authority="Treitschke, 1825" authorityName="Treitschke" authorityYear="1825" box="[853,1013,1014,1038]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Bryophila" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="145" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="miltophaea">
<emphasis box="[853,1013,1014,1038]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="145">B. miltophaea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the shield-like juxta with almost parallel lateral sides (
<taxonomicName authority="Treitschke, 1825" authorityName="Treitschke" authorityYear="1825" box="[409,571,1051,1075]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Bryophila" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="145" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="miltophaea">
<emphasis box="[409,571,1051,1075]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="145">B. miltophaea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has longer, medially constricted juxta) and the larger cornutus; from 
<taxonomicName authority="Treitschke, 1825" authorityName="Treitschke" authorityYear="1825" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Bryophila" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="145" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="plumbeola">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="145">B. plumbeola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by its long, digitiform clasper (
<taxonomicName authority="Treitschke, 1825" authorityName="Treitschke" authorityYear="1825" box="[624,773,1086,1110]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Bryophila" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="145" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="plumbeola">
<emphasis box="[624,773,1086,1110]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="145">B. plumbeola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has short, thick clasper). The female genitalia (
<figureCitation box="[1305,1387,1086,1111]" captionStart="FIGURES 7 – 11" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1864,1887]" captionTargetBox="[153,1415,195,1840]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,195,1843]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 7 – 11. Bryophila spp., male and female genitalia. 7, B. kaszabi, male genitalia, holotype, slide OP 2222 m Pekarsky; 8, B. miltophaea, male genitalia, slide OP 0163 m Pekarsky; 9, B. plumbeola, male genitalia, holotype, slide MB 244 Boursin; 10, B. kaszabi, female genitalia, paratype, slide OP 0626 f Pekarsky; 11, B. miltophaea, female genitalia, slide OP 0164 f Pekarsky." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/230794/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="145">
Fig. 
<number box="[1358,1387,1087,1111]" pageId="2" pageNumber="145" value="10.0">10</number>
</figureCitation>
) are very similar to those of 
<taxonomicName authority="Treitschke, 1825" authorityName="Treitschke" authorityYear="1825" box="[420,578,1123,1147]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Bryophila" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="145" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="miltophaea">
<emphasis box="[420,578,1123,1147]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="145">B. miltophaea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[594,676,1122,1147]" captionStart="FIGURES 7 – 11" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1864,1887]" captionTargetBox="[153,1415,195,1840]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,195,1843]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 7 – 11. Bryophila spp., male and female genitalia. 7, B. kaszabi, male genitalia, holotype, slide OP 2222 m Pekarsky; 8, B. miltophaea, male genitalia, slide OP 0163 m Pekarsky; 9, B. plumbeola, male genitalia, holotype, slide MB 244 Boursin; 10, B. kaszabi, female genitalia, paratype, slide OP 0626 f Pekarsky; 11, B. miltophaea, female genitalia, slide OP 0164 f Pekarsky." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/230794/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="145">
Fig. 
<number box="[647,676,1123,1147]" pageId="2" pageNumber="145" value="11.0">11</number>
</figureCitation>
), there are no remarkable differences in female genitalia structures, but the subgenital plate (
<number box="[428,442,1162,1186]" pageId="2" pageNumber="145" value="8.0">8</number>
th abdominal segment) of the new species is wider.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="145" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,258,1981]" pageId="2" pageNumber="145">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,431,1197,1222]" pageId="2" pageNumber="145">Description. Adults</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[446,548,1197,1222]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 6" captionStartId="1.[151,264,1789,1812]" captionTargetBox="[191,1413,212,1759]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[151,1436,195,1765]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 6. Bryophila spp., adults. 1, B. kaszabi, holotype male, W Mongolia, Hundijn-Gol riv. (OPB); 2, B. kaszabi, paratype female, W Mongolia, Uenchijn-Gol riv. (AVB); 3, B. kaszabi,, paratype female, Hundijn-Gol riv. (AVB); 4, B. plumbeola, after Hampson (1908); 5, B. miltophaea, male, Kyrgyzstan, Naryn (ZISP); 6, B. miltophaea, male, Kyrgyzstan, Alai Mts. (OPB)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/230793/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="145">
Figs 
<number box="[503,548,1198,1222]" pageId="2" pageNumber="145" value="2.0" valueMax="3.0" valueMin="1.0">1–3</number>
</figureCitation>
). Wingspan 
<quantity box="[688,813,1198,1222]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.95" metricValueMax="3.0" metricValueMin="2.9" pageId="2" pageNumber="145" unit="mm" value="29.5" valueMax="30.0" valueMin="29.0">29–30 mm</quantity>
. Head, collar, thorax, tegulae and abdomen pale yellow irrorated with dark scales. Abdomen pale yellow. Forewing elongated; apex finely pointed; outer margin with straight upper part (from apex to vein M 
<number box="[608,621,1270,1294]" pageId="2" pageNumber="145" value="3.0">3</number>
) and oblique lower part (from vein M 
<number box="[1051,1063,1270,1294]" pageId="2" pageNumber="145" value="3.0">3</number>
to vein A 
<number box="[1181,1192,1270,1294]" pageId="2" pageNumber="145" value="1.0">1</number>
). Ground colour light pale yellow irrorated with dark scales that makes the general view brown; subbasal and medial areas dark; wing pattern well developed; basal field as ground colour; antemedial line slightly oblique and rather straight with small curve at base; medial field dark with small light area in the middle as ground colour; postmedial line oblique, sinuous; subterminal line distinct; terminal line fine, marked by small black streaks; pre-apical patch trapezoidal; reniform and orbicular stigma dark edged by brown scales along outer margin; claviform stigma absent; cilia as ground colour. Hindwing uniformly dark, ochreous-grey; discal spot traceable. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1074,1248,1485,1510]" pageId="2" pageNumber="145">Male genitalia</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[1267,1339,1485,1510]" captionStart="FIGURES 7 – 11" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1864,1887]" captionTargetBox="[153,1415,195,1840]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,195,1843]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 7 – 11. Bryophila spp., male and female genitalia. 7, B. kaszabi, male genitalia, holotype, slide OP 2222 m Pekarsky; 8, B. miltophaea, male genitalia, slide OP 0163 m Pekarsky; 9, B. plumbeola, male genitalia, holotype, slide MB 244 Boursin; 10, B. kaszabi, female genitalia, paratype, slide OP 0626 f Pekarsky; 11, B. miltophaea, female genitalia, slide OP 0164 f Pekarsky." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/230794/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="145">
Fig. 
<number box="[1323,1339,1486,1510]" pageId="2" pageNumber="145" value="7.0">7</number>
</figureCitation>
). Uncus relatively short, laterally flattened, somewhat S-shaped with small but strong apical hook, tegumen shorter than vinculum; transtilla narrow, half-ring-like; juxta shield-like with almost parallel lateral edges; valva long, narrow, costal edge straight, dorsal margin constricted at middle with elongated pointed apex; clasper long, thin, rather digitiform, bent two times. Aedeagus short, cylindrical with strong carinal plate; vesica small, globular, membranous, finely scobinated at base; basal diverticulum small; medial diverticulum large, subsphaerical with large spine-like cornutus; terminal tube long, wide at base, tapering distally. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1002,1199,1701,1726]" pageId="2" pageNumber="145">Female genitalia</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[1213,1294,1701,1726]" captionStart="FIGURES 7 – 11" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1864,1887]" captionTargetBox="[153,1415,195,1840]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,195,1843]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 7 – 11. Bryophila spp., male and female genitalia. 7, B. kaszabi, male genitalia, holotype, slide OP 2222 m Pekarsky; 8, B. miltophaea, male genitalia, slide OP 0163 m Pekarsky; 9, B. plumbeola, male genitalia, holotype, slide MB 244 Boursin; 10, B. kaszabi, female genitalia, paratype, slide OP 0626 f Pekarsky; 11, B. miltophaea, female genitalia, slide OP 0164 f Pekarsky." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/230794/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="145">
Fig. 
<number box="[1265,1294,1702,1726]" pageId="2" pageNumber="145" value="10.0">10</number>
</figureCitation>
). Ovipositor large, wide, densely covered with hair-like setae; anterior apophyses long, posterior apophyses slightly shorter and thinner than anterior apophyses. Ostium bursae short, broad, ventral plate very narrow; subgenital plate (
<number box="[1410,1424,1776,1800]" pageId="2" pageNumber="145" value="8.0">8</number>
th abdominal segment) wide, well sclerotized; ductus bursae short with large lateral wrinkled and semi-sclerotized formation located oppositely to small, membranous appendix bursae; corpus bursae rounded, membranous, scobinate.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="145" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,258,1981]" pageId="2" pageNumber="145">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,544,1920,1945]" pageId="2" pageNumber="145">Distribution and bionomics.</emphasis>
The new species is known from several localities in Khovd aimak, southwestern 
<collectingCountry box="[245,358,1956,1981]" name="Mongolia" pageId="2" pageNumber="145">Mongolia</collectingCountry>
. 
<taxonomicName authority="Treitschke, 1825" authorityName="Treitschke" authorityYear="1825" box="[368,483,1956,1980]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Bryophila" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="145" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="kaszabi">
<emphasis box="[368,483,1956,1980]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="145">B. kaszabi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
inhabits dry rocky and stony steppe biotopes (
<figureCitation box="[1005,1088,1956,1981]" captionStart="FIGURE 12" captionStartId="4.[151,250,948,970]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,926]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,193,926]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 12. SW Mongolia, Khovd aimak, Bodonchijn-Gol basin, Hundij-Gol riv. valley, 46 ° 06 ' N, 92 ° 30 ' E, 3. vii. 2010, type locality of B. kaszabi (Photo byR. V. Yakovlev)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/230795/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="145">
Fig. 
<number box="[1057,1088,1957,1981]" pageId="2" pageNumber="145" value="12.0">12</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
